The **root cause** is that in the **H2 database some data types are synonym**, but [hibernate currently does not handle this fact][1]. 

There is [another stackoverflow question targeting a similar issue][2] with H2 returning a synonym type instead of the expected one.

A [workaround is proposed in the related hibernate bugtracker ticket][1]. Just implement a **custom hibernate H2 dialect** which may look like this:

    package your.pckg.name;
    
    import java.sql.Types;
    import org.hibernate.dialect.H2Dialect;
    
    public class H2DialectCustom extends H2Dialect {
    
        public H2DialectCustom() {
            super();
            registerColumnType(Types.BINARY, &quot;varbinary&quot;);
        }
    
    }

and *register it in your hibernate/JPA settings*:

&gt; spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.dialect = your.pckg.name.H2DialectCustom


  [1]: https://hibernate.atlassian.net/browse/HHH-9835
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42907617

I complete agree with the [answer given by AntiTiming](https://stackoverflow.com/a/43093800/3447566).
 
Another possible workaround is to specify the column definition explicitly on the UUID property of the JPA entity:

    public class Entity {

        @Column(columnDefinition = &quot;varbinary not null&quot;)
        private UUID uuid = UUID.randomUUID();

    }

