So I think this question is a bit in the weeds, the gist is that `volatile` indicates that the value of the variable may change outside the scope of the current thread, and that its value must always be read before use.

In principle, the statement you&#39;re quoting is really saying that prior to replacing the value with the current thread, the value will be read.

Your example is a race condition, both threads may return true, neither may return true, or they may each return a different value -- the semantics of `volatile` won&#39;t define execution for your example (I&#39;d encourage you to compile and run it and see that the output varies).

A common way to illustrate the behavior of `volatile` is to run two threads, where one thread updates shared state and to see what happens when the field is marked, and when it isn&#39;t:

    class VolatileTest implements Runnable
    {
            // try with and without volatile
            private volatile boolean stopRunning = false;
            
            public void triggerStop(){
                 stopRunning = true;
            }
     
            @Override
            public void run(){
                 while(!stopRunning);
                 System.out.println(&quot;Finished.&quot;);
            }
     
            public static void main (String[] args) throws java.lang.Exception
            {
                final VolatileTest test = new VolatileTest();
                new Thread(test).start();
                Thread.sleep(1000);
                test.triggerStop() = false;
            }
    }

In this example, failure to mark `stopRunning` as `volatile` can lead to the `while` loop continuing forever, as unless `stopRunning` is marked as `volatile` it&#39;s not required to read the value on each iteration.

I think you have a bad example here.  Both threads can get into the else block quite easily (thread 0 reads x &amp; checks against 1, then thread 1 reads y and checks against 1).

The example of interest is something like this:

    thread 0          thread 1

    x = 1             y = 1
    if (y == 0) {     if (x == 0) {
    }                 }

Both threads cannot get into the `if` block if `x` and `y` are volatile.

&gt;**Volatile guarantees visibility, synchronization guarantees both visibility and atomicity**

Only guarantee it provides is if `x` or `y` updated by one thread then update will be visible to all the threads.
The order of execution solely depends on how your threads are running. The answer to context switch question is no since comparison happens before entering so it will be only one time and it will be based on value of variable at that time. This might possible if you have multiple comparisons for the same variable.


The best way to use volatile is for maintaining state variables of the class. Where in any new assignment will reflect in all threads which are accessing that class

If you look at the source code of  `ThreadPoolExecutor` several state variables are volatile.

One of them happens to be `runState` which determines state of the `ThreadPoolExecutor`. Now when `shutdown()` is called `runState` is updated to `SHUTDOWN`  so that methods which accepts the task which are `execute` `submit` stops accepting the task which happens to be a simple `if(runState==RUNNING)`

Below code is `execute` method of [ThreadPoolExecutor](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/ThreadPoolExecutor.html)

In below code if you see no additional synchronization is needed for `poolSize`, `runState` variables because they are volatile state variables.


    public void execute(Runnable command) {
        if (command == null)
            throw new NullPointerException();
        if (**poolSize** &gt;= corePoolSize || !addIfUnderCorePoolSize(command)) {//poolSize  volatile
            if (**runState** == RUNNING &amp;&amp; workQueue.offer(command)) {//runstate volatile
                if (**runState** != RUNNING || **poolSize** == 0)//runstate volatile
                    ensureQueuedTaskHandled(command);
            }
            else if (!addIfUnderMaximumPoolSize(command))
                reject(command); // is shutdown or saturated
        }
      }


**When not to use it?**

&gt;When variable needs to be used in atomic operations or when one variable value depends on another variable value  e.g. Increment i++.

**Alternative**
&gt;Atomic variables are called as **better volatile** which has memory semantics as volatile but provide you additional operations. e.g. incrementAndGet() operation provided by AtomicInteger.

